{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525956","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525956"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:19:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:19:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14105"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14105","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14105"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.3,0.54,0.07,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6775"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55926"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6775","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6775"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14105"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41475"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"163"},{"type":"tags","id":"2902"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14874"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36143"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36145"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43486"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55926"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for a follow-up appointment regarding his gout management. He was diagnosed with gout two years ago. He reports having no gout flares in the past three months. He has a medical history of hypertension and obesity. His regular medications include allopurinol (300mg daily for the past six months) and amlodipine. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are no visible tophi or joint swelling.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate serum urate target for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["\u003C0.26 mmol/L","\u003C0.30 mmol/L","\u003C0.36 mmol/L","\u003C0.40 mmol/L","\u003C0.46 mmol/L"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate serum urate target for this patient with gout is \u003Cstrong\u003E\u0026lt;0.36 mmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E. This target is widely accepted as the therapeutic goal in gout management, as it helps prevent gout flares and reduces the formation of tophi.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u0026lt;0.26 mmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E is an unnecessarily low target that may be difficult to achieve and maintain. While it would certainly prevent gout flares, it might require higher doses of urate-lowering therapy, potentially increasing the risk of side effects without providing additional clinical benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u0026lt;0.30 mmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E is also lower than the generally accepted target. While it would be effective in preventing gout flares, it is not necessary to aim for this lower level in most patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u0026lt;0.40 mmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E is slightly higher than the recommended target. While it may be sufficient for some patients, aiming for \u0026lt;0.36 mmol/L provides a better safety margin for preventing urate crystal formation and gout flares.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u0026lt;0.46 mmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E is too high as a target for effective gout management. At this level, there is still a risk of urate crystal formation and gout flares.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to note that achieving and maintaining the target serum urate level often requires ongoing monitoring and adjustment of urate-lowering therapy. In this case, the patient is on allopurinol 300 mg daily, which may need to be adjusted based on his serum urate levels. Regular follow-up and serum urate testing are essential to ensure that the target is being maintained and to adjust treatment as necessary.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The target serum urate level for gout management is \u003C0.36 mmol/L.","Achieving and maintaining this target level helps prevent gout flares and reduces tophi formation. Regular monitoring of serum urate levels is essential for effective gout management."],"references":["Robinson P, Stamp L. The management of gout: Much has changed. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2016;45:299-302. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2016/may/the-management-of-gout-much-has-changed"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41475"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14105"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41475","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41475"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-18T15:35:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-15T20:05:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6775"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55926"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null}